\subsection{Cursors: [[dot]] and [[dol]]}
%alt: Addresses? Line Pointers?

%claude:
[[dot]] and [[dol]] are pointers into the [[zero]] array.
Their names match the ed command syntax: [[dot]] is the {current line}
(what the user refers to as~[[.]]), and [[dol]] is the {last line}
(what the user refers to as~[[$]], ``dollar'').
Both are pointers, not indices: [[dot - zero]] gives the
current line number, and [[dol - zero]] gives the total number
of lines.  When the buffer is empty, [[dol == zero]].

<<globals ed.c>>=
// ref<int> in zero array, current line pointer
int*    dot;
// ref<int> in zero array, last line pointer
int*    dol;
@
% those are called dot and dol, which seems cryptic, but
% they match the symbol used to describe those entities in the editor
% itself with $ (dollar) marking end of file and dot the current line.
% The user will enter '$' and '.' in commands.

%yoann: can actually reference motivation section and script where was using 1,$ for range of lines
%claude:
This is where the [[1,$]] address range from the [[mkenam]] script
in Section~\ref{sec:motivations-mkenam} comes from.
The substitute command in that script means ``from line~1 to [[$]]
(the last line), substitute \ldots''---and now we know that [[$]] is
just the user spelling for [[dol]]. Similarly, the [[.]] in commands
like [[.s/old/new/]] refers to [[dot]].

%Classic ed addresses include:
%- 0 (before first line)
%- 1
%- .
%- $

% note that dol is zero when empty file (not even a single line)

