\subsection{Notes/signals management}

%claude:
\plan uses {notes} instead of \unix signals.
On an ``interrupt'' note, [[ed]] prints a newline and
jumps back to the command loop via [[notejmp]] (the \plan
equivalent of [[siglongjmp]]).
On a ``hangup'' note (terminal disconnected), it calls
[<rescue()>], which saves the buffer to [[ed.hup]] before
exiting---a safety net so you do not lose unsaved work.

%claude: %plan9-is-cleaner:
The difference between \plan notes and \unix signals is worth
spelling out because it affects what an [[ed]]-like program
can do in the handler. Signals on \unix are delivered
asynchronously by the kernel, identified by a small integer
([[SIGINT]], [[SIGHUP]], \ldots), and the handler runs on the
current stack with very few things it is allowed to touch
(see the ``async-signal-safe'' list in [[signal(7)]]).
Notes on \plan, by contrast, are \emph{strings}
([[{}"interrupt"{}]], [[{}"hangup"{}]], [[{}"sys: ..."{}]]) that
the kernel writes to [[/proc/$pid/note]]; the receiving process
reads them out via its registered [<notifyf()>] callback and
decides what to do by calling [[noted(NCONT)]] (resume) or
[[noted(NDFLT)]] (default action).
\begin{verbatim}
   \unix signals              \plan notes
   ------------------------   -------------------------------
   int id (SIGINT, SIGHUP)    string ("interrupt", "hangup")
   kernel async delivery      kernel writes /proc/$pid/note
   handler on the same stack  handler via notified user thread
   sigjmp_buf + siglongjmp    Label + notejmp (same idea)
   SA_RESTART / EINTR dance   restartable by default; noted()
   limited to async-safe fns  fewer restrictions in practice
\end{verbatim}
%
For [[ed]] specifically, three things follow from being on
\plan. First, the handler can [[strcmp]] the string instead
of switching on an integer, which is why [<notifyf()>] starts
with [[strcmp(s, "interrupt")]]. Second, [[notejmp]] replaces
[[siglongjmp]]: it restores the [[Label]] saved by [[setjmp]]
and then tells the kernel the note has been handled. Third,
the [[rescuing]] and [[waiting]] flags exist to short-circuit
recursive notes: if an interrupt arrives while we are already
saving [[ed.hup]], or while [[callunix]] is blocked in
[[waitpid]], we do not want to restart the save or kill the
child---we just call [[noted(NCONT)]] and resume.

<<globals ed.c>>=
bool rescuing;
@

<<function [[notifyf]](ed.c)>>=
void
notifyf(void *a, char *s)
{
    if(strcmp(s, "interrupt") == ORD__EQ){
        if(rescuing || waiting)
            noted(NCONT);
        putchr(L'\n');
        lastc = '\n';
        error_1(Q);
        notejmp(a, savej, 0);
    }
    if(strcmp(s, "hangup") == ORD__EQ){
        if(rescuing)
            noted(NDFLT);
        rescue();
    }
    fprint(STDERR, "ed: note: %s\n", s);
    abort();
}
@
% notejmp??

<<function [[rescue]](ed.c)>>=
void
rescue(void)
{
    rescuing = true;
    if(dol > zero) {
        addr1 = zero+1;
        addr2 = dol;
        io = create("ed.hup", OWRITE, 0666);
        if(io > 0){
            Binit(&iobuf, io, OWRITE);
            putfile();
        }
    }
    fchange = false;
    quit();
}
@

